{{see|latino}}

==English==

===Etymology===
From {{Sp.}} ''[[latino#Spanish|latino]]'' {{pos_a}} < {{Sp.}} ''[[latinoamericano]]'' (Latin American) < {{L.}} ''[[latinus]]'' (pertaining to [[Latium]], the region of Italy around Rome), possibly from Proto-Indo-European base '''*stela-''' (to spread, to extend, hence flat country as opposed to mountainous).

===Proper noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A male Latin Person. Speakers of any of the world's Romance languages spoken in Europe or America. synonymous with Latin.
#:''The Latin(o)s were enjoying the rehearsal for their upcoming Latin jazz concert.
===Adjective=== 
# American Spanish adjective latino (feminine: latina) directly translates to English as Latin. Any of the world's Romance languages spoken in Europe or America, or speakers of these languages. i.e.Spaniards view themselves as being Latino, the same as Italians, Romanians, French, Portuguese and people of the Americas who are speakers these languages

